ave had a considerable earnings\nslump and whose business outlook\nI for the next few months is uncertain.\nI Among these were stocks of the\ni leather concerns, some of the ship\nping shares and one or two of the\nsugars. National I'ioak and Suit,\nwhich had begun to break toward the\niclose of last week fell sharply again,\nwhile the Independent stat?- stocks were\nunder pressure on the idea that the\nsteel trade has not yet had its due re\naction in comparison with other indus\ntries.\nBank Fig-area SutUfj.\nPredictions on the Saturday bank\nreturns went ridiculously astray, ft\nwas supposed that they would show\na greatly weakened position. On the\ncontrary, the New York Hank was\nable to report a gain of nearly 1 per\ncent in its reserve ratio proper and\nof over 2 per cent in the reserve ratio\nafter deducting 4t> per cent against\nfederal reserve notes.\nThis makes up the loss of the last\ntwo weeks at New York, while the\nposition in the country as a whole has\nnot been impaired. The ratio of the\ntwelve regional institutions combined\nwas slightly higher at the close of\nlast week than it was the week be\nfore, and this despite the fact that the\ncrop-moving strain is now at its\nheight.\nThe great advantage of the federal\nreserve system in distributing the\nburden of this strain is becoming more\nand more apparent all the time, de\nspite the criticism leveled against it.\nThe banks at Boston and Cleveland\nhelped out the banks at New- York and\nChicago, with the result that the Bos\nton ratio came down front 46.3 to 44.6.\nthe Cleveland ratio from 48.6 to 46.S.\nwhile the ratio at New York went up\nfrom 38.6 to 39.5, and at Chicago from\n42.4 to 43.7.\nHtMhc Their Otra.\nIt was interesting to note that in the\ncotton and grain districts the reserve\nbanks held their own, and this in the\ntry ing second week of September was an\nimportant achievement. The banking\nposition at large was sustained by the\ngold arrivals, which were sufficient to\noffset the currency expansion Incident to\ncrop demands. Inasmuch as these gold\narrivals will be still larger from now\non?tt.ono.ooo more came in at New York\ntoday?this tendency should be still more\npronounced for the next few weeks than\nit was last week.\nU. S. RIDERS 'WAY DOWN.\nSeventh and Obstacle Bice. Fifth\nin Hurdles in Olympics.\nANTWERP. September IS.?In the j\nobstacle race for horsemen, held in\nconnection with the Olympic games,\nthe individual prise was won by Lieut.\nLequio of Italy. Maj. Vaierio of Italy\nwas second and Capt. Lewenhaupt of\nSweden third.\nThe American competitors finished\nas follows: (\"apt. Allen, seventh:\nMaj. Downer, twelfth, and Maj. West,\neighteenth.\nIn the hurdles competition Sweden\nwon first place with 14 points. Bel\ngium was second with 16.25, Italy\nthird with 18.75, France fourth with I\n34.75 and the United States fifth\nwith 42.\nFOREIGN BONDS.\nQuotation! furnished by W. B. Bibb* it t>.\nPrices at noon:\nBerlin 4* 19 German gov. 3'-a* 14'*i\nGreater Berlin 4s German gov. 4s. 1 !-j\nBremen 2114 Germon gov. 5s. 18\nC'hemnilz 4s 30 Krupp 4* 2Ua\nfoblenz 4? 22 Bad. Aniline 4'..s 24\nCologne 4? 21 Al. HI. Ges. 4ij? 22'i\nl>?nzir 4s 23 Mein'ger Bonk 4s 21'n\nDarmstadt 4s.... Nord. Lt Bank 4s 21\nDresden 4s 1 ft'^ Preuss Bank 4s.. 21!?>\nIfresden 4>as.... ^1 Berliner Bank 4s. 21^\nI>uss?ldorf 4s.... 19f^i Vienna 4* .\"i.10\nFss*n 4* 20?~ Vienna 4'$* 5.70\nFrankfurt 4*.... 21 Vienna 5s 6.SO\nFrankfurt 5s 25 French 4? 4#li,\nHamburg 3s 14Vi I'reneh 3a.. HI\nHamburg 3'is... 15'.., French prem. 5s. 71U\nHamburg 4s 18'^ British Tie. 4s....272\nHambun; 4Jis... 'Sli? Nat. wor loan 5s.357\nKuenigsberg 4s.. 1# War loan 5s 302\nLeipzig 4'-is Vt'4 Italian 5s 37\nI^ipeig 5s 22' j Italian note* 1025 45\nMunich 4s -1 l-j Belgian rent. 5s-.. 72\nGerman gov. 3s.. 14 Belgian prem. 5s. 76\nFREIGHT RATES STAND.\nCanadian Government Declines te\nStay Ruling Granting Increase.\nOTTAWA. September 13. The\nDominion government, in an official\nstatement, declined to grant a stay In\nthe ruling of the board of railway\ncommissioners which authorized the\nrailways to increase freight, passen\nger and sleeping car rates. The order\ngoes into effect today.\nThe government, however, recog\nnized the right of appeal against the\nruling and. it was announced, would\nfacilitate an early hearing.\nCENSUS IN THREE STATES.\nFigures Given for Places in North\nCarolina, Alabama and Mississippi.\nThe following- figures were an\nnounced by the census baftatt today:\nEDUCATIONAL.\nLaw School\nOpta* Oct. 1\n3-1 ear tonne t'lse and l?tW?k\nMethod.\nAccountancy\nDegree (.ranting Power\n'area for I\". P. A. and Baa;\nest and Oldeat School la\nPreparatory\nAccredited Hani*\nVlephone or Write for Ot\n.\\ew .'(O-Pufe Bulletin\nStenography\n5tdO Clauses Start\n*KPTKMBKK 1\nDrafting\nal. Arehlteetaral,\nmtti\n-Y. M. C. A. .H.\nMechaaleal. Architectural, $.VM> a\nawn\nITS*\nSt. V\nMala\nUN\ni\nThe Thrill That Comet Once in t Lifetime.\n?By WeWter.\nAlabama places?Sulligent, 1.071; In- increase. S. Indiariola, -.112; increase,\ncrease. 452. Tuskegee. 2,473; decrease. 1.014. Moorhead. 1.600: increase, 594. j\nS2S. Altceville, 044; increase. 304. I Ruleville. 1,022; increase. 571. i\nUeform. 1.069; increase, 019. Haleys- North Carolina places?Ohadbourn,\nville. 1.404; increase. 293. 904; decrease. :>38. Whiteville, 1.664;;\nMississippi placfcs?Houston. 1,40!; increase. 296. I\nPLANS FOR COFFEE TRADE\nSteamship Company Schedules\nWeekly Sailings.\nBALTIMORE, September 13.?Plans\nhave been completed by the Green Stat\nline officials for the establishment of\nweekly sailing* of steamers from this\nport in the South American coffee trade.\nThe schedule will require the operation\nof eight ships in this trade. With the\ncarrying out of the present plan Balti\nmore will again become the principal\nport for the receipt of coffee imports in\nthis country. This is the position it I\nheld many years ago, when during the\nperiod the large fleet of Baltimore\nclippers were engaged in bringing cof\nfee here from South America.\nFollowing this development in steam\nship activities, there will be a reopen\ning of numerous other industries con\nnected with the coffeev trade, such as\nthe putting into operation of the grind\ning mills and roasting plants, as but a\nsmall quantity of the coffee received j\nhere by steamers will be shipped in the\ngreen state. The large majority of the\ncoffee will be roasted here and the\ngreater portion of this will be ground\nand packed into tins before being ship- j\nped to other points. j\nOIL STOCKS.\nQuotation* furnished by W. B. HIfobs Co.)\nBid. Aftktd.\nAnglo-American Oil Co. (new).. 21 Va 22 Vj\nAtlantic Refining Co 1150 1225\nnorne-Scrymser Co 110 425\nHuckeye Pipe Line Co 93 90 I\nCheseborough-Mfcnufacturing Co. 220 230\nContinental Oil Co 120 125\nCrescent Pipe Line Co 80 32\nCumberland Pipe Line 135 145\nKureka Pipe Line 105 110\nGalena-Signal Oil Co. com 47 50\nGalena-Signal Oil Co. pTd 00 95\nIllinois Pipe Lino Co 153 157\nIndiana Pipe Lino Co s7 92\nNational Transit Co 20 28\nNew York Transport at ion Co..?% 105 175\n.Northern Pipe Line Co 98 102\nOhio Oil Co 815 325\nPennsylvania-Mexican Fuel 13 40\nPrairie Oil and Gas Co 540 550\nPrairie Pipe Line Co 193 197\nSolar Refining Co 370 390\nSent hern Pipe Line Co 122 128\nSouth Penn. Oil Co 207 272 1\nSouthwest.. Penn. Pipe Line Co.. 03\nStandard Oil Co. California 310 315\nStandard Oil Co. Indiana BOO K70\nStandard Oil Co. Kansas 7?25 545\nStandard Oil Co. Kentucky 350 370\nStandard Oil Co. Nebraska 420 440\nStandard Oil Co. New York.... 384 388\nStandard Oil Co. Ohio 430 450\nSwan Finch Co 70 80\nt.'nion Tank Line Co 120 124\nVacuum Oil Co 3.-5 3?o\nWashington Oil Co ^9 33\n\nSeveral hundred new vari?ti*8 in\npenny toys are brought out every\nweek by makers in London.\nFRENCH REVENUE GROWS.\n1980 Receipts to Sate Exceed Esti\nmates by 8,176,574,600 Francs.\n.PARIS, September 11.?The ministry\nof ftnance announced todav t